data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in `Span<T>` conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent calls to span-based methods**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime (`NotSupportedException`).

## How to fix it

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or using `.AsEnumerable()`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

All three prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the call within what expression trees can represent.
